V. THE RE GARD.

ONcE in every three years an inspection of the woods within the metes and bounds of the forests was or ought to have been made by twelve knights chosen for the purpose. The inspection was called by the author of the ‘Dialogus de Scaccario’ the ‘uisitatio3 nemo- rum‚’ but it was commonly, even in the twelfth century, known as the Regard. The duty of the twelve knights who were called regarders⁴ was to find answers to a set of interrogatories entituled the Chapters of the Regard. Although they appear to have varied in form from time to time during the reigns of Henry IL, Richard L, and John, they acquired a rigid form early in the reign of Henry HL, which they retained throughout the reigns of the three kings who succeeded him.
